{"cursor":"10901","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"'Triphosphates' are salts or esters of polymeric oxyanions formed from\ntetrahedral PO 4 (phosphate) structural units linked together by\nsharing oxygen atoms. When two corners are shared the polyphosphate may have a\nlinear chain structure or a cyclic ring structure. In biology the polyphosphate\nesters AMP, ADP and ATP are involved in energy transfer. A variety of\npolyphosphates find application in mineral sequestration in municipal waters,\ngenerally being present at 1 to 5 pm. http://www.jacksmagic.-\ncom/pdfs/FAQ_phosphates.pdf GTP, CTP, and UTP are also nucleotides\nimportant in the protein synthesis, lipid synthesis and carbohydrate metabolism,\nrespectively.\n\n\n","linknr":204,"url":"triphosphate","recorded":1362557229,"links":26,"instances":["chemistry","chemistry"],"pdf":["http://www.jacksmagic.com/pdfs/FAQ_phosphates.pdf"],"categories":["Phosphates","Polymers"],"headings":["Structure & Formation","Acid-base and complexation properties","The \"high energy\" phosphate bond","High-polymeric inorganic polyphosphates","See also","References","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a9/Triphosphors%C3%A4ure.svg/180px-Triphosphors%C3%A4ure.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ee/Polyphosphoric_acid.svg/180px-Polyphosphoric_acid.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/67/Trimetaphosphat.svg/133px-Trimetaphosphat.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/22/Adenosindiphosphat_protoniert.svg/180px-Adenosindiphosphat_protoniert.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/96/Equilibrium.svg/15px-Equilibrium.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/96/Equilibrium.svg/15px-Equilibrium.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/3/0/a/30a83899d43b156384be84db854210fd.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/96/Equilibrium.svg/15px-Equilibrium.svg.png","//upload.wikime